This Talk

(I was told that summary slides are helpful, so here's a summary slide)
  • We're going to start by describing a major flaw in the design of ranges
    • Like all things C++, it has a catchy barely-pronounceable name: TPOIASI
  • We'll get to the bottom of what's causing this problem
    • We're going to do it the Daisy way: by diving deep into a lot of code
    • …real, standard library code (🚨🚨🚨)
  • We're going to talk about a solution to this problem that involves turning ranges "inside-out"
    • And then we're going to implement some of these live
    • Finally we'll talk briefly about what this could mean for the future of C++

"The Terrible Problem Of Incrementing A Smart Iterator"

We're invoking the transform_view's __func_ in both filter_view::operator++() and filter_view::operator*()!

Is filter_view broken?


  • Anything that dereferences the underlying iterator somewhere other than operator*() is going to have this problem
    • drop_while
      • (in drop_while_view::begin())
    • take_while
      • (in sentinel_t<take_while_view>::operator==())
    • chunk_by
  • …or anything that dereferences the same element more than once...
    • slide
    • set_difference
    • is_permutation

Is laziness the problem?

(i.e., "If developers don't understand functional programming, can't we just teach them?")

Let's think about v | transform(f) | slide(n):

How many times is f(3) evaluated?

  • If f is "expensive", the author of this code probably doesn't understand that f isn't evaluated until it's needed ("evaluated lazily")
    • We can argue about whether or not that's a reason to disallow ranges in large-scale software engineering context

Is transform(f) | filter(g) the same problem?

Question: when is the result of f(2) "needed"?

  • It depends on how lazy you are!
  • The latest possible time when you need the result of f(2) is right before you have to print it
  • The "surprise" here comes from eagerly evaluating iterator_t<filter_view>::operator++() before we know when (or if) iterator_t<filter_view>::operator*() is going to be called!
    • This is the most important point in this presentation
    • This is a different "flavor" of surprise than not understanding laziness generally

What if we wait until we know what we're going to do with the result of f(2) before we call it?

What have we learned about output iterator composition?

  • Output iterator composition is an "inside-out" version of the views in std::ranges
  • Both push and pull models can be lazy
  • Push models work around TPOIASI by merging the output iterator analogs of the increment and dereference operations into one customization point
    • But this simply doesn't work for some use cases. For instance:
      • reverse
      • sort (or anything else that's multipass)
      • slide (can be done, but it's awkward)
    • There are also some use cases that simply don't work with a pull model
      • Flattened one-to-many transforms (e.g., flat_map; can be done, but it's a lot more awkward)
  • Push-style composition can exist alongside pull-style composition
    • This is a good thing! It means we could have both in the standard library one day (maybe)
